===Etymology===
Existing in English since the sixteenth century: from {{L.}} ''[[#Latin|pancreas]]'', from {{AGr.}} '''{{polytonic|[[πάγκρεας]]}}''' {{italbrac|pankreas}}, from '''{{polytonic|[[παν-]]}}''' {{italbrac|pan-}}, “[[pan-#English|pan-]], [[all#English|all]]-” + '''{{polytonic|[[κρέας]]}}''' {{italbrac|kreas}}, “[[flesh]]”.<ref name="COED-etym">The '''Concise Oxford English Dictionary''' [Eleventh Edition]</ref>

===Pronunciation===
* {{UK}} {{IPA|/ˈpæŋkɹɪəs/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|pancreases|pl2=pancreata}}

# {{anatomy}} A gland near the [[stomach]] which secretes a fluid to help with food digestion and also the hormone insulin which helps the body process glucose (or sugars).

